Yesterday Jack and I flew down to NASA to watch the candidate selection. There’s nothing quite like seeing the best and brightest step forward to carry America’s mission of exploration into the future. 

It was an honor to be there, and I couldn’t be more proud that Texas continues to play such a big role in our nation’s space story.

Its always special for me to be back at the U.S. Naval Academy, the place where my own journey of service began. Every time I walk those grounds again and visit with today’s midshipmen, it reminded me of my own time there. They’re sharp, motivated, and ready to serve our nation.

I left feeling proud and encouraged.

This week, we heard from President Salome Zourabichvili, former Minister of Defense Tinatin Khidasheli, and Luke Coffey of the Hudson Institute. We agreed that Vladimir Putin is the enemy and discussed the global consequences of Georgia’s turn away from democratic values. 

The United States stands with the people of Georgia.

Like many of you, I have a vivid memory of where I was and what I was doing on that fateful morning 24 years ago. It was one of the greatest tragedies our nation has ever faced. As I remember that day, I also remember what happened afterward: we united, we came together, and we stood tall.

Though we may have dark times in our history, our country is exceptional, chosen by our Creator to be the shining light on the hill. We will never be broken. We will always prevail. Ecclesiastes 1:9 says, “There is nothing new under the sun.” Every generation faces great challenges, but our brighter days are ahead. A bright future is on the horizon.

Had a great time stopping by DY Concrete in Alvarado to visit with their team and learn more about the work they’re doing. 

A big thank you to Joe and Jason Delehay for the warm welcome and for showing me around. It’s always great to see local businesses thriving and providing opportunities here in our community.

My office is hosting Q&A sessions in Corsicana, Midlothian, and Palestine this September for students, parents, and teachers to learn more about the application and nomination process.

Come join us and see how these academies can open the door to a lifetime of service and leadership.

It was great to be in Red Oak this morning to celebrate Qarbon Aerospace and the Boeing team for their work on the T-7A Red Hawk. For more than 60 years, the T-38 trained generations of Air Force pilots. Now, the T-7A will carry that legacy forward. 

And it’s all built right here in Texas.

There are a lot of things I expected when I was elected to Congress, but touring a Walmart was not on my bingo card. Just when you think you’ve seen it all in a store you’ve probably walked through thousands of times, you end up learning something new. A big thank you to the Walmart in Mansfield for inviting me on an tour!

Last night, I spoke in support of the Fiscal Year 2026 Defense Appropriations Act. I support this because it invests in our military superiority, it shapes a more efficient and effective Department of Defense, protects our southern border, and takes care of our troops and their families.

We avoid war by ensuring that our enemy knows that we will win. This bill does that.

As we continue to keep the folks of Kerr County in our prayers, Texans from across the state are working tirelessly to help save lives.

If you have any information, please call (830) 258-1111.

We won’t stop. These are our friends, our neighbors, and our loved ones. We’re keeping the faith, lifting up our prayers, and holding onto hope.

As families of fallen heroes gather in our nation’s capital this week, it’s a powerful reminder of the bravery and dedication of those who serve our communities. Some give everything, and others stand ready to act in moments that matter most.

Today, I had the opportunity to ask Secretary Kennedy some questions. I was encouraged to hear that the Department of Health and Human Services is working closely with other agencies to rectify past wrongs, that the department's direction is being turned around, and that they're taking ownership of past mistakes and working to correct them moving forward. I appreciate the Secretary's willingness to work with Congress and answer some tough questions. 

I left encouraged by progress being made and look forward to continuing an open dialogue with the Secretary.

Had a great conversation this evening in Washington with @VeteransOnDuty. The defense of our nation is not up for debate. The number one job of any government is the protection of its people, and while in Congress, I will do all I can to ensure the federal government fulfills that duty.

This week, as family members of fallen heroes gather in our nation’s capital, we are reminded of the sacrifices made to keep our communities safe. Their courage and dedication are etched into the fabric of our nation, and we owe them a debt that can never truly be repaid.

To those who have left us, thank you for your sacrifice. To those who carry their memory forward, thank you for keeping their legacy alive.

It will propose a $3,000 annual tax credit to employers for hiring and retaining registered apprentices in key occupations critical to our nation's infrastructure, with an enhanced credit of $6,000 for members of our armed services.

It's over! Today, Secretary Duffy and the U.S. Department of Transportation rescinded the grant funding for Texas Central's High-Speed Rail Boondoggle. Through numerous conversations and collaboration with the Secretary, it became clear that we share a commitment to ensuring that projects like this do not misuse federal resources, and today is a result of those conversations.

I was honored to preside over the House when the SAVE Act passed. This legislation demonstrates the kind of leadership Americans expect from us. With strong bipartisan support, we’ve moved one step closer to ensuring that our borders remain secure and our immigration system is enforced effectively. I will continue working alongside my colleagues to make sure this bill gets across the finish line in the Senate.

Government spending has been out of control for too long, and the American people sent us to Washington to rein it in—not make it worse. House Republicans just delivered on another promise. 

It was a privilege to be in the chair as we passed the Trump-backed budget that unlocks his full agenda: extending tax cuts for hardworking families and small businesses, increasing funding for border security, and delivering historic savings for taxpayers.

While I've been working in Washington to dismantle Texas Centrals' High-Speed Rail project at the federal level, my friends in Austin have been taking action on the state level. This week, after learning just how much of a boondoggle this project really is, the Texas House Committee on Transportation voted to subpoena Texas Central, compelling them to produce crucial documents—documents they clearly don't want the public to see.

I'm grateful for the leadership of Chairman @CodyforTexas, Chairman Craddick, Representative Little, Representative Patterson, and all the members of the Transportation Committee for taking this important step.

Last week, I had the opportunity to attend a special event at the Luxembourg Embassy in Washington, where we paid tribute to the survivors of the Battle of the Bulge. This pivotal battle, fought from December 1944 to January 1945, was the last major German offensive on the Western Front during WWII. It resulted in approximately 19,000 American deaths, with countless others wounded or missing. Their courage and sacrifice during one of WWII's toughest battles are a testament to the strength of the human spirit. We must always remember and honor their service.

Veterans Day always makes me stop and think about the Privilege, Service, and Sacrifice of our veterans. Every service member has a unique story, but we all share one thing in common: the privilege of serving this great country. We raised our right hands, swore an oath, and gave a part of ourselves to defend and protect the freedoms we hold dear. And we did it willingly, knowing full well that service would ask a lot from us—and our families.

The sacrifices of military life are different for each person, but they’re no less real. For me, as a Navy guy, service meant long hours on the flight line, days spent getting ready for missions that would take me into the sky or out on the water. There were plenty of thrills, but there were also the long hours of prepping and debriefing, making sure every part of the aircraft was good to go, and taking care of the young sailors who worked hard to make it all happen. Every mission, every day, was a reminder that service isn’t just about the big moments—it’s about the daily grind and the commitment to something bigger than yourself.

Today is a day to say “thank you” to all those who served, who made it through and came back home to build their lives alongside the rest of us. For me, that means spending time with my wife and kids, enjoying the freedoms our veterans fought for and making up for some of the time I missed while I was standing watch.

So, if you see a veteran today, take a minute to thank them. For what they did, for who they defended, and for the country they served.
To my fellow brothers and sisters in arms, happy 249th birthday!

In 1918, when Mansfield residents donated the original funds to construct Memorial Hall to honor World War I veterans, they could have never imagined what it would become. It was truly an honor to be there today as they broke ground. This facility will be a testament to the sacrifices of those before us who gave their lives for the freedoms we enjoy today.
